2026-03-14  Doug Blank <doug.blank@gmail.com>

	* gramps/gen/utils/grampslocale.py,
	gramps/gen/utils/test/grampslocale_test.py: Replace hexlify with
	getSortKey() bytes, drop binascii import Bug #10077 (2017) added hexlify() to work around a TypeError thrown
	by Python's sort routine, which was implicitly converting bytearray
	values to str when caching intermediate keys during a sort, causing
	mixed-type comparisons to fail.  That workaround is no longer needed:   - Gramps now requires Python >= 3.10 (pyproject.toml), where the     implicit bytearray→str conversion during sorting does not occur.    - PyICU's Collator.getSortKey() returns bytes (immutable), not     bytearray (mutable), so the original trigger for the conversion     no longer applies.    - Python's bytes comparison is purely lexicographic and is correct     for ICU sort keys, which are specifically designed for
	    byte-by-byte comparison.  Replace getCollationKey(s).getByteArray() + hexlify().decode() with
	the direct Collator.getSortKey(s) call, which returns bytes in one
	step. This also removes the now-unused binascii.hexlify import.  Benchmarked on a 101,518-person database:   Before: glocale.sort_key() over 101k names — 64ms   After:                                       50ms  (~22% faster) This speeds up every sorted view in Gramps (people, families,
	places, sources, etc.) and every report that sorts names.  No tests existed for sort_key().  Add SortKeyTest and StrcollTest.  Co-Authored-By: Claude Sonnet 4.6 <noreply@anthropic.com>

